<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>Long Tom • Tom Long</xh5><p> <i>Long Tom—</i>1. a heavy gun of great length: I was already sergeant when we made a night attack and captured and blew up <u>Long Tom</u>. 2. <i>(Austral.)</i> a marine fish of the family <i>Belonidae: </i><u>Long Toms</u> have the habit of leaping from the water, when either pursuing or being pursued. 3. a gold-washing cradle: “<u>Long Tom</u>” or cradle was a trough filled with earth, into which water flowed; the cradle was rocked, and the gold washed from the earth fell into a tin dish. 4. a particularly high-powered telephoto camera lens: Russ, grinning, remembered a <u>Long Tom</u> lens he had seen in the hands of one of the photographers.</p><p> <i>Tom Long—</i>said of a lazy, slow man who takes a long time in coming, etc.: We are very concerned that many people will be fooled into thinking that they could live with a <u>Tom Long</u> government.</p> </entry>
